extends /views/templates/layouts/_base

append variables
	- pagetitle = "PanelControl | Examples | Wizard"

block content
	.lane
		.container
			.page-header
				h1 Wizard
				p.lead A multi-step flow with per-step validation. PanelControl owns the tab UI, the page owns only the flow.

	+section("Live demo")
		p The PanelSet #[a(href="/panelset/examples/wizard.html") Wizard] builds its tab strip and locking by hand, and ends on a hint: that repetitive work "belongs in a small reusable tab-strip layer over PanelSet." This page is that layer. PanelControl handles the tab clicks, keyboard navigation, roving #[code tabindex], and the #[code aria-disabled] locking; PanelSet handles the Previous / Next buttons (#[code data-ps-prev] / #[code data-ps-next]) and disables them at the ends. What is left on the page is purely #[strong flow]: validate a step, allow or block a forward move, and decide which tabs to lock.

		p A required checkbox on each step controls whether you can move on. Because tab clicks, #[code next()], #[code prev()], keyboard and deep links all funnel through #[code show()], a single #[code ps:beforeactivate] listener guards every path. Stepping #[strong back] is always allowed.

		.card
			.demo
				nav.tabs#pcwiz-tabs(role="tablist" data-panelcontrol aria-label="Steps")
					button(role="tab" aria-controls="pcwiz-step-1" aria-selected="true") Account
					button(role="tab" aria-controls="pcwiz-step-2" data-pc-disabled-hint="pcwiz-lock-hint") Profile
					button(role="tab" aria-controls="pcwiz-step-3" data-pc-disabled-hint="pcwiz-lock-hint") Confirm

				#pcwiz(data-panelset data-ps-levels).tab-content
					.panel-wrapper
						.active#pcwiz-step-1(role="tabpanel" aria-label="Account")
							h3 Step 1. Account
							label.wizard-check
								input(type="checkbox" required)
								span I agree to create an account
						#pcwiz-step-2(role="tabpanel" hidden aria-label="Profile")
							h3 Step 2. Profile
							label.wizard-check
								input(type="checkbox" required)
								span I confirm my profile details are correct
						#pcwiz-step-3(role="tabpanel" hidden aria-label="Confirm")
							h3 Step 3. Confirm
							label.wizard-check
								input(type="checkbox" required)
								span I accept the terms and conditions

				.wizard-nav
					button.secondary(data-ps-prev="#pcwiz" data-ps-disabled-hint="pcwiz-prev-hint") Previous
					button(data-ps-next="#pcwiz") Next
				span#pcwiz-lock-hint(hidden) Complete the earlier steps before this one.
				span#pcwiz-prev-hint(hidden) You’re on the first step.
				span#pcwiz-next-hint(hidden) You’re on the last step.
				span#pcwiz-next-incomplete-hint(hidden) Complete this step to continue.

			p #[strong Try it]: with the current step unticked, #[strong Next] is disabled (focus it to hear why) and the later tabs stay locked. Tick the box and #[strong Next] enables and the next tab unlocks. A tab further ahead stays locked until you reach it.

			p Every disabled control here explains itself, and #[em why] it is disabled decides who owns the hint. #[strong Position] (you are at an end) is PanelSet’s: #[strong Previous] carries #[code data-ps-disabled-hint], attached on the first step. #[strong Validation] (a step is incomplete) is flow’s: the locked tabs use #[code data-pc-disabled-hint] (applied by PanelControl), and #[strong Next], which can be blocked either way, has its hint set by the flow script: "last step" at the end, "complete this step" when the current step is unticked. Because the default #[code disabledMode] is #[code aria], every disabled control stays focusable, so a keyboard or screen-reader user lands on it and hears the reason (the hint rides #[code aria-describedby] only while the control is disabled, never on an enabled one).

			h4 Markup
			+codeblock('HTML')
				nav.tabs(role="tablist" data-panelcontrol aria-label="Steps")
					button(role="tab" aria-controls="pcwiz-step-1" aria-selected="true") Account
					button(role="tab" aria-controls="pcwiz-step-2" data-pc-disabled-hint="pcwiz-lock-hint") Profile
					button(role="tab" aria-controls="pcwiz-step-3" data-pc-disabled-hint="pcwiz-lock-hint") Confirm
				+n
				#pcwiz(data-panelset data-ps-levels)
					.panel-wrapper
						#pcwiz-step-1.active(role="tabpanel")
							label
								input(type="checkbox" required)
								span I agree to create an account
						#pcwiz-step-2(role="tabpanel" hidden) …
						#pcwiz-step-3(role="tabpanel" hidden) …
				+n
				.wizard-nav
					button(data-ps-prev="#pcwiz" data-ps-disabled-hint="pcwiz-prev-hint") Previous
					button(data-ps-next="#pcwiz") Next
				span#pcwiz-lock-hint(hidden) Complete the earlier steps before this one.
				span#pcwiz-prev-hint(hidden) You’re on the first step.
				span#pcwiz-next-hint(hidden) You’re on the last step.
				span#pcwiz-next-incomplete-hint(hidden) Complete this step to continue.

	+section("The flow logic")
		p PanelControl handles tab activation, keyboard navigation, roving, and the #[code aria-disabled] reflection; PanelSet handles the Previous / Next buttons and disables them at the ends. Both are driven by the markup alone. The page adds only flow:

		+codeblock('JS').
			const strip = document.querySelector('#pcwiz-tabs');
			const pc    = strip.panelControl;        // set by PanelControl.init()
			const setEl = document.querySelector('#pcwiz');
			const tabs  = [...strip.querySelectorAll('[role="tab"]')];
			const nextBtn = document.querySelector('[data-ps-next="#pcwiz"]');

			const panelOf = tab => document.getElementById(tab.getAttribute('aria-controls'));
			const valid   = panel => !panel.querySelector('[required]:invalid');

			// Hard rule: one listener covers every path into show() (tab clicks,
			// the data-ps-prev/next buttons, and keyboard).
			setEl.addEventListener('ps:beforeactivate', e => {
				const { outgoingPanel, targetPanel } = e.detail;
				const forward = outgoingPanel &&
					(outgoingPanel.compareDocumentPosition(targetPanel) & Node.DOCUMENT_POSITION_FOLLOWING);
				if (forward && !valid(outgoingPanel)) {
					e.preventDefault();
					outgoingPanel.querySelector('[required]:invalid')?.focus();
				}
			});

			// Soft state: lock steps beyond the first incomplete one, and disable Next
			// until the current step is valid. PanelSet disables Next at the last step;
			// this adds the validation rule (and, since the button stays focusable,
			// sets its hint to match the reason it is disabled).
			function refresh() {
				const firstInvalid = tabs.findIndex(t => !valid(panelOf(t)));
				tabs.forEach((t, i) => pc.setTabState(
					t.getAttribute('aria-controls'),
					firstInvalid !== -1 && i > firstInvalid ? 'disabled' : 'enabled'
				));
				const i = tabs.findIndex(t => t.getAttribute('aria-controls') === setEl.panelSet.getActive());
				const atEnd = i === tabs.length - 1;
				const incomplete = i >= 0 && !valid(panelOf(tabs[i]));
				nextBtn.setAttribute('aria-disabled', String(atEnd || incomplete));
				const hint = atEnd ? 'pcwiz-next-hint' : incomplete ? 'pcwiz-next-incomplete-hint' : '';
				if (hint) nextBtn.setAttribute('aria-describedby', hint);
				else nextBtn.removeAttribute('aria-describedby');
			}
			setEl.addEventListener('change', refresh);
			setEl.addEventListener('ps:activationcomplete', refresh);
			refresh();

		p Next to the #[a(href="/panelset/examples/wizard.html") hand-built PanelSet version], the tab click handlers, the keyboard logic, and the whole Previous / Next block (setup and end-disabling) are gone. Stepping is now markup (#[code data-ps-prev] / #[code data-ps-next], disabled at the ends by PanelSet), and locking goes through #[code setTabState()] (which also keeps the roving #[code tabindex] correct) instead of poking #[code aria-disabled] directly. What stays on the page is the validation and the lock policy. That is a clear split: #[strong PanelControl and PanelSet own the UI, the page owns the flow].

	+section("Rough edges")
		p Two rough edges show on purpose:
		ul
			li #[strong A locked tab’s click is silent.] A focused locked tab now explains itself (#[code data-pc-disabled-hint] adds an #[code aria-describedby] note while it is locked), but #[em clicking] one still does nothing and says nothing. The #[strong Next] button, by contrast, goes through the #[code ps:beforeactivate] check and focuses the missing field.
			li #[strong Arrow keys skip locked tabs.] A locked tab leaves the roving order, so arrows jump over it. For a wizard you might prefer to arrow #[em onto] a locked step to read it, while still refusing to activate it. That is a design choice, not a fixed rule.


append styles
	style.
		#pcwiz {
			--ps-panel-in-transform-from: translateX(40px);
			--ps-panel-out-transform-to:  translateX(-40px);
			--ps-panel-in-delay: 0s;
		}

		.wizard-nav {
			display: flex;
			justify-content: space-between;
			gap: 0.5rem;
			margin-top: 0.75rem;
		}
		.wizard-check {
			display: flex;
			align-items: center;
			gap: 0.5rem;
			margin-top: 0.75rem;
		}
		.tabs [role="tab"][aria-disabled="true"],
		.wizard-nav [aria-disabled="true"] {
			opacity: 0.4;
			cursor: not-allowed;
		}


append scripts
	if isProd
		script(src=`${basePath}lib/panelset.js` vite-ignore)
		script.
			PanelControl.init();
			PanelSet.init();
		script(src=`${basePath}assets/scripts/example-pcwizard.js` vite-ignore)
	else
		script(type="module").
			import { PanelSet, PanelControl } from 'panelset';
			PanelControl.init({ debug: true });
			PanelSet.init({ debug: true });
		script(type="module" src="/src/assets/scripts/example-pcwizard.js")
